## Website Content Recommendations

Based on the above, here's how to structure their website:

### Homepage (Hero Section)
Lead with energy. A full-width dark background with **live show footage or a performance photo**, overlaid with the band name in their signature chunky hand-lettered font style. The headline should be punchy and in their voice — something like **"We make songs you'll play on repeat (and covers you forgot you loved)"** or simply **"The Filibusters — Pop-Punk. Covers. Chaos."** Include a prominent CTA button: **"Stream 'Break Up With Your Boyfriend'"** and a secondary one for **"Watch Us Live."**

### Music / Singles Section
Highlight their original music front and center with embedded Spotify/Apple Music players. Feature "Break Up With Your Boyfriend" as the hero release with cover art, stream links, and a short one-liner about the song. Keep the copy casual and fun, matching their IG tone — avoid formal press-release language.

### Covers & Mashups Section
This is a big part of their identity and what gets engagement. Embed YouTube or Reels of their best covers (Paramore, OneRepublic "Secrets," pop-punk medleys). Title this section something like **"Our Covers Hit Different"** to keep the voice consistent.

### Shows / Tour Section
Even if they're playing local or college shows, list upcoming events. Use a dark, grungy gig-poster aesthetic similar to their Battle of the Bands flyers. Text like **"Come see what the chaos looks like in person"** fits their vibe perfectly.

### About / Band Section
Keep it short, fun, and personal — not a formal bio. Something like a casual introduction to each member with a photo and one funny/quirky fact. Lean into the "we're just your friends who happen to be in a band" energy that comes through their Instagram. Mention the cello — it's distinctive and worth highlighting.

### Color Palette & Typography Suggestions
- **Background:** Deep black or very dark charcoal
- **Accent colors:** Hot pink, electric yellow, and cobalt blue (all present in their IG graphics)
- **Typography:** A bold, retro-chunky display font for headers (something in the style of their "Full Cover" text overlays), paired with a clean sans-serif for body text
- **Overall vibe:** Edgy but playful — think late-2000s pop-punk revival meets current Gen-Z internet aesthetics

### What to Avoid
Don't go overly polished or corporate — their appeal is their raw, authentic, slightly chaotic energy. A website that feels too "industry professional" would clash with the brand they've built on Instagram.